# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: charles-palache
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:charles-palache/alice-palache-jones] Alice Helen Palache was born in Cambridge, Massachusetts, the daughter of Charles Palache and Helen Harrington Markham Palache.
[src:charles-palache/alice-palache-jones] Her father was a Harvard professor and mineralogist; her mother was a teacher.
[src:charles-palache/alice-palache-jones] Palache graduated from Bryn Mawr College in 1928, and was close to her classmate, Katharine Hepburn.
[src:charles-palache/alice-palache-jones] The two women traveled in Europe together as students.
[src:charles-palache/alice-palache-jones] At Bryn Mawr, she played tennis, basketball, and field hockey.
[src:charles-palache/alice-palache-jones] She was also active in dramatics and glee club, and president of the Undergraduate Association in her senior year.
[src:charles-palache/alice-palache-jones] Palache was executive director of the National Committee on Federal Legislation for Birth Control from 1930 to 1933, working with Margaret Sanger.
[src:charles-palache/alice-palache-jones] In 1933, she began working at the Fiduciary Trust Company of New York as a trainee.
[src:charles-palache/alice-palache-jones] She worked at the Fiduciary Trust Company until her retirement in 1974, as senior vice president of the company.
[src:charles-palache/alice-palache-jones] During World War II, she was the company's acting chief executive.
[src:charles-palache/alice-palache-jones] She was also director of the Dreyfus Third Century Fund.
[src:charles-palache/alice-palache-jones] Later in life, Jones was a trustee of the North Salem Free Library, a member of the board of directors of Bryn Mawr College, and chair of the North Salem Planning Board.
[src:charles-palache/alice-palache-jones] Palache married advertising executive and cookbook author Russell Kennedy Jones in 1954, as his second wife; they met in 1932.
[src:charles-palache/alice-palache-jones] She died age 82 on June 12, 1989, in Mount Kisco, New York.
[src:charles-palache/alice-palache-jones] Some of her papers are in the Palache Family Papers at Harvard's Schlesinger Library.
[src:charles-palache/alice-palache-jones] Her niece was editor Judith Palache Gregory.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The **American Academy of Arts and Sciences** (**The Academy**) is one of the oldest learned societies in the United States.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It was founded in 1780 during the American Revolution by John Adams, John Hancock, James Bowdoin, Andrew Oliver, and other Founding Fathers of the United States.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It is headquartered in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Membership in the academy is achieved through a nominating petition, review, and election process.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy's quarterly journal, *Dædalus*, is published by the MIT Press on behalf of the academy, and has been open-access since January 2021.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy also conducts multidisciplinary public policy research.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Patton has served as President of the Academy since January 2025.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The first class of new members, chosen by the Academy in 1781, included Benjamin Franklin and George Washington as well as several international honorary members.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The initial volume of Academy *Memoirs* appeared in 1785, and the *Proceedings* followed in 1846.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the 1950s, the Academy launched its journal *Daedalus*, reflecting its commitment to a broader intellectual and socially-oriented program.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Since the second half of the twentieth century, independent research has become a central focus of the Academy.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the late 1950s, arms control emerged as one of its signature concerns.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The Academy also served as the catalyst in establishing the National Humanities Center in North Carolina.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the late 1990s, the Academy developed a new strategic plan, focusing on four major areas: science, technology, and global security; social policy and education; humanities and culture; and education.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In 2002, the Academy established a visiting scholars program in association with Harvard University.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] More than 75 academic institutions from across the country have become Affiliates of the Academy to support this program and other Academy initiatives.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The Academy has sponsored a number of awards and prizes, throughout its history and has offered opportunities for fellowships and visiting scholars at the Academy.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In July 2013, *The Boston Globe* exposed then president Leslie Berlowitz for falsifying her credentials, faking a doctorate, and consistently mistreating her staff.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It is modeled on the Science and Engineering Indicators, published biennially by the National Science Board as required by Congress.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Ever since the founding of the Academy, its members have been nominated and elected by peers.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Members of the Academy included not only scientists and scholars, but also writers and artists as well as representatives from the full range of professions and public life.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Throughout the Academy's history, more than 10,000 fellows have been elected.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Astronomer Maria Mitchell was the first woman elected to the Academy, in 1848.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The current membership encompasses over 5,700 members based across the United States and around the world.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Academy members include more than 250 Nobel laureates and more than 60 Pulitzer Prize winners.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Of the Academy's 14,343 members since 1780, 1,406 are or have been affiliated with Harvard University, 611 with the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, 433 with Yale University, 425 with the University of California, Berkeley, and 404 with Stanford University.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The following table includes those institutions affiliated with 300 or more members.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] † Excludes members affiliated exclusively with associated national laboratories.
[src:charles-palache/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] As of 2023, membership is divided into five classes and thirty specialties.
[src:charles-palache/american-journal-of-science] The ***American Journal of Science*** (***AJS***) is the United States of America's longest-running scientific journal, having been published continuously since its conception in 1818 by Professor Benjamin Silliman, who edited and financed it himself.
[src:charles-palache/american-journal-of-science] It was initially called the ***American Journal of Science and Arts*** until a name change in 1880, but its focus was always on natural sciences and especially on geology and related subjects.
[src:charles-palache/american-journal-of-science] In early years, the journal was often referred to as "Silliman's Journal", and the publication became associated with Yale University due to his long tenure there (1804–1853).
[src:charles-palache/american-journal-of-science] The editorship long remained in the family of Professor Silliman, as he was assisted by his son, Benjamin Silliman Jr., from 1838.
[src:charles-palache/american-journal-of-science] On the death of the elder Silliman in 1864, he was succeeded as chief editor by his son-in-law, James Dwight Dana, and then from 1895 till 1926 by Dana's son Edward Salisbury Dana.
[src:charles-palache/american-journal-of-science] Associate editors included the botanist Asa Gray and the zoologist Louis Agassiz.
[src:charles-palache/american-journal-of-science] The current editors are Mark Brandon Yale University, C.
[src:charles-palache/american-journal-of-science] Page Chamberlain Stanford University, Louis Derry Cornell University, Francis Macdonald UC Berkeley, and Ann Pearson Harvard University.
[src:charles-palache/benjamin-kendall-emerson] Emerson attended Amherst College, where he joined the Alpha Delta Phi fraternity and from which he graduated in 1865 as valedictorian.
[src:charles-palache/benjamin-kendall-emerson] He went on to study in Germany at the University of Berlin, and received his doctorate from the University of Göttingen in 1870.
[src:charles-palache/benjamin-kendall-emerson] He returned to the United States where he joined the faculty at Amherst, where he was professor of geology and related sciences from 1872 to 1917 and simultaneously at Smith College from 1878 to 1912.
[src:charles-palache/benjamin-kendall-emerson] He was also assistant geologist from 1890 to 1896, and later geologist from 1896 to 1920 for the United States Geological Survey.
[src:charles-palache/benjamin-kendall-emerson] He helped found the Geological Society of America and was its president in 1899.
[src:charles-palache/benjamin-kendall-emerson] In 1893 he was seriously injured in a train wreck in Ohio, but he recovered.
[src:charles-palache/benjamin-kendall-emerson] In 1897 he was elected vice president of the International Geological Congress, and attended the meeting of the Congress in St Petersburg, Russia.
[src:charles-palache/benjamin-kendall-emerson] He followed this with an excursion through Siberia.
[src:charles-palache/benjamin-kendall-emerson] In 1899 he accompanied the Harriman Alaska Expedition, where Mount Emerson bears his name.
[src:charles-palache/benjamin-kendall-emerson] His chief field of study was the geology of western Massachusetts, the Connecticut River valley, and Rhode Island.
[src:charles-palache/benjamin-kendall-emerson] Benjamin Kendall Emerson was the son of Benjamin Frothingham Emerson and Eliza Kendall Emerson of Nashua, New Hampshire.
[src:charles-palache/benjamin-kendall-emerson] He married twice; his first wife was Mary Annette Hopkins, daughter of Rev Erastus Hopkins of Northampton, Massachusetts.
[src:charles-palache/benjamin-kendall-emerson] They were married on April 2, 1873, and had six children: Charlotte Freylinghuysen (b.
[src:charles-palache/benjamin-kendall-emerson] 1887), and Caroline Dwight (1891-1973), who became a prolific author of over 20 children's books, including *The Hat-Tub Tale*, about the Bay of Fundy.
[src:charles-palache/benjamin-kendall-emerson] Mary Annette Hopkins Emerson died on July 3, 1897; Benjamin Emerson then married Anna James Seelye, daughter of Julius Seelye of Amherst on April 4, 1901.
[src:charles-palache/benjamin-kendall-emerson] They had two children: Elizabeth James (b.
[src:charles-palache/benjamin-kendall-emerson] Among his works are *Geology of Old Hampshire County, Massachusetts* (1898), *Geology of Massachusetts and Rhode Island* (1917), and a report (1904) on the Harriman Expedition to Alaska.
[src:charles-palache/benjamin-kendall-emerson] The Archives and Special Collections at Amherst College holds a collection of his papers.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder is located at the base of the foothills of the Rocky Mountains, at an elevation of 5,430 feet (1,655 m) above sea level.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The city is 25 miles (40 km) northwest of the Colorado state capital of Denver.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder is a college town, hosting the University of Colorado Boulder, the flagship and largest campus of the University of Colorado system, as well as numerous research institutes.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Starting in 2027, Boulder will become the new home of the Sundance Film Festival.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Archaeological evidence shows that Boulder Valley has been continuously inhabited by Native American tribes for over 13,000 years, beginning in the late Pleistocene era.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Throughout the Paleo-Indian, Archaic, and Late Prehistoric periods, indigenous peoples moved seasonally between the mountains and plains, taking shelter in winter along the Front Range trough where Boulder now lies.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] By the 1500s, the Ute people held primary occupation of Boulder Valley.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In the early 1800s, the Arapaho migrated to the region.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Additional Native American nations with historical ties to the broader Front Range include the Apache, Arapaho, Cheyenne, Comanche, Kiowa, Pawnee, Shoshone, Sioux, and Ute peoples.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In the 1800s, European Americans settled in the area.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder was founded in late 1858 when prospectors led by Thomas Aikins arrived at Boulder Canyon during the Colorado Gold Rush.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] According to historical accounts, they initially camped in an area historically associated with Arapaho leader Chief Niwot, though the Arapaho's stable settlement had been displaced by earlier treaty obligations.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Under the Treaty of Fort Wise (1861), the Arapaho were formally forced to relocate to the Cheyenne-Arapaho Reservation.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Some of these early settlers later participated in the 1864 Sand Creek massacre, where Niwot himself was killed.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In early 1859, gold was discovered along Boulder Creek, drawing more miners and merchants to the area.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The Boulder City Town Company was formed in February 1859 to establish a settlement at the canyon mouth.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The Boulder, Nebraska Territory, post office opened on April 22, 1859.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] On August 24, 1859, voters of the Pike's Peak mining region approved the formation of the Provisional Government of the Territory of Jefferson, and on November 28, 1859, the extralegal Jefferson Territory created Jackson County with Boulder City as its seat.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] By 1860, Boulder City had 70 cabins, occupied mainly by Anglo families.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Chinese miners and Black residents lived in early Boulder but experienced systematic marginalization and were largely absent from contemporary photographs and official records, reflecting the racial hierarchies of the era.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The free Territory of Colorado was organized on February 28, 1861, and Boulder County was created on November 1, 1861, with Boulder City as its seat.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The Arapaho were forced to relocate by the Treaty of Fort Wise.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] With declining numbers, Niwot's band soon moved to the Cheyenne-Arapaho Reservation.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] By 1862, the creek had yielded $100,000 in gold, and Boulder's population exceeded 300.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] On November 7, 1861, the Colorado General Assembly passed legislation to locate the University of Colorado in Boulder.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The City of Boulder City was incorporated on November 4, 1871.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] On September 20, 1875, the first cornerstone was laid for the first building (Old Main) on the CU campus.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Colorado became a state on August 1, 1876, and the university officially opened on September 5, 1877.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The City of Boulder City shortened its name to the City of Boulder.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In 1907, Boulder adopted an anti-saloon ordinance.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In 1916, statewide prohibition started in Colorado, and ended with the repeal of national prohibition in 1933.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In 2024, the City Council of Boulder repealed a long-standing law that prevented Boulder from increasing new residential units by more than 1% in a year.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In 1959, city voters approved the "Blue Line" city-charter amendment, which restricted city water service to altitudes below 5,750 feet (1,750 m), to protect the mountain backdrop from development.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In 1967, city voters approved a dedicated sales tax to acquire open space to contain urban sprawl.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In 1970, Boulder created a "comprehensive plan" to dictate future zoning, transportation, and urban planning decisions.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In 1972, the city enacted a height-limiting ordinance for buildings to preserve views of the Flatirons and surrounding mountains.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] This ordinance remains in effect and continues to shape Boulder's skyline and downtown development patterns.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In 1974, a Historic Preservation Code was passed.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In 1976, a *residential-growth management* ordinance, the Danish Plan, was passed.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The city of Boulder is located in the Boulder Valley, where the Rocky Mountains meet the Great Plains.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The Flatirons, slabs of sedimentary stone tilted up on the foothills, are located west of the city and are a widely recognized symbol of Boulder.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder Creek is the primary flow of water through Boulder.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The creek was named before the city's founding and its etymology is unknown.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] It is from Boulder Creek that the city is believed to have taken its name.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder Creek has significant water flow, derived primarily from snow melt and minor springs west of the city.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Vrain Creek east of Longmont, which is a tributary of the South Platte River.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] At the 2020 United States census, the city had a total area of 17,514 acres (70.877 km2), including 664 acres (2.689 km2) of water.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The 40th parallel, 40 degrees north latitude, runs through Boulder and can be easily recognized as Baseline Road today.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder lies in a wide basin beneath Flagstaff Mountain just a few miles east of the continental divide and about 25 miles (40 km) northwest of Denver.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Arapahoe Glacier provides water for the city, along with Boulder Creek, which flows through the center of the city.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Denver International Airport is located 33 miles (53 km) east-southeast of Boulder.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In 1899, government preservation of open space around Boulder began, with the Congress of the United States approving the allocation of 1,800 acres (7.3 km2) of mountain backdrop and watershed extending from South Boulder Creek to Sunshine Canyon.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder has created an Urban Wildlife Management Plan which sets policies for managing and protecting urban wildlife.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The city's Parks and Recreation and Open Space and Mountain Parks departments have volunteers who monitor parks, including wetlands, lakes, etc., to protect ecosystems.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] From time to time, parks and hiking trails are closed to conserve or restore ecosystems.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Traditionally, Boulder has avoided using chemical pesticides to control the insect population.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] However, with the threat of West Nile virus, the city began an integrative plan to control the mosquito population in 2003 that includes chemical pesticides.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Residents can opt out of the program by contacting the city and asking that their areas not be sprayed.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Under Boulder law, exterminating prairie dogs requires a permit.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In 2005, the city experimented with using goats for weed control in environmentally sensitive areas.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Goats naturally consume diffuse knapweed and Canada thistle, and although the program was less effective than expected, goats will still be considered in future weed control projects.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In 2010, goats were used to keep weeds under control at the Boulder Reservoir.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The city's Open Space and Mountain Parks department manages approximately 8,000 acres (32 km2) of protected forest land west of the city, in accordance with a 1999 Forest Ecosystem Management Plan.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The plan aims to maintain or enhance native plant and animal species, their communities, the ecological processes that sustain them and to reduce the wildfire risk to forest and human communities.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder has a temperate climate typical for much of the state and receives many sunny or mostly sunny days each year.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder is considered semi-arid (Köppen: *BSk*) or humid subtropical (Köppen: *Cfa*) within the Köppen climate classification due to its relatively high yearly precipitation and average temperatures remaining above 32 °F (0 °C) year-round.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Winter conditions range from generally mild to the occasional bitterly cold.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Highs average in the mid to upper 40s °F (7–9 °C).
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] There are 4.6 nights annually where the temperature drops to 0 °F (−18 °C).
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Because of orographic lift, the mountains to the west often dry out the air passing over the Front Range, shielding the city from precipitation in winter, though heavy snowfalls may occur.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Snowfall averages 88 inches (220 cm) per season.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Due to the high elevation, a strong warming sun can quickly melt snow cover during the day and Chinook winds bring rapid warm-ups throughout the winter months.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Summers are warm, with frequent afternoon thunderstorms.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] There are roughly 30 days of 90 °F (32 °C) or above each year.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Diurnal temperature variation is typically large due to the high elevation and semi-arid climate.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Daytime highs are generally cooler than those of most Colorado cities with similar elevations.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The highest recorded temperature of 104 °F (40 °C) was on June 25, 2012.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The coldest high temperature, −12 °F (−24 °C), was on February 4, 1989.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder is the principal city of the Boulder, CO Metropolitan Statistical Area.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In the 2010 census, there were 97,385 people, 41,302 households, and 16,694 families in the city.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The population density was 3,942.7 inhabitants per square mile (1,522.3/km2).
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] There were 43,479 housing units at an average density of 1,760.3 units per square mile (679.7 units/km2).
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The racial makeup of the city was 88.0% White, 0.9% Black or African American, 0.4% Native American, 4.7% Asian, 0.1% Pacific Islander, 3.2% some other race, and 2.6% from two or more races.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] 8.7% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] There were 41,302 households, of which 19.1% had children under 18 living with them, 32.2% were headed by married couples living together, 5.5% had a female householder with no husband present, and 59.6% were non-families.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] 35.8% of all households comprised individuals, and 7.1% were someone living alone who was 65 or older.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The average household size was 2.16, and the average family size was 2.84.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder's population is younger than the national average, largely due to the presence of university students.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The median age at the 2010 census was 28.7 years compared to the U.S. median of 37.2 years.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] For every 100 females, there were 105.5 males.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] For every 100 females age 18 and older, there were 106.2 males.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In 2011, the estimated median household income in Boulder was $57,112, and the median family income was $113,681.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Male full-time workers had a median income of $71,993 versus $47,574 for females.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The per capita income for the city was $37,600.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] 24.8% of the population and 7.6% of families were below the poverty line.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Out of the total population, 17.4% of those under 18 and 6.0% of those 65 and older were living below the poverty line.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In 2010, the Boulder MSA had a gross metropolitan product of $18.3 billion, the 110th largest metropolitan economy in the United States.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In 2007, Boulder became the first city in the United States to levy a carbon tax.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In 2013, Boulder appeared on *Forbes* magazine's list of Best Places for Business and Careers.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder has hosted a 10 km road run, the Bolder Boulder, on Memorial Day every year since 1979.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The race involves over 50,000 runners, joggers, walkers, and wheelchair racers, making it one of the largest road races in the world.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] It has the largest non-marathon prize purse in road racing.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The race culminates at Folsom Field with a Memorial Day Tribute.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The 2007 race featured over 54,000 runners, walkers, and wheelchair racers, making it the largest race in the US in which all participants are timed and the fifth largest road race in the world.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Founded in 1958, the Boulder Philharmonic Orchestra is a professional orchestra under the leadership of its Music Director Michael Butterman.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Founded in 1976 by Giora Bernstein, the Colorado Music Festival presents a summer series of concerts in Chautauqua Auditorium.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Founded in 1981, the Boulder Bach Festival is an annual festival celebrating the life, legacy, and music of J.S.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The festival is led by Executive Director Zachary Carrettin and Artistic Director Mina Gajić.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Founded in 1988, Colorado MahlerFest celebrates the legacy of composer Gustav Mahler through an annual festival.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Under Artistic Director Kenneth Woods, The Colorado MahlerFest Orchestra draws together young professionals, conservatory and university students, and advanced amateurs.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder is home to multiple dance companies and establishments.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder Ballet was founded by former American Ballet Theatre dancer Larry Boyette in the 1970s as part of the Ballet Arts Studios.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Lemon Sponge Cake Contemporary Ballet was founded in 2004 by Robert Sher-Machherndl, former principal dancer of the Dutch National Ballet and Bavarian State Ballet.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The Conference on World Affairs, started in 1948, is an annual one-week conference featuring dozens of discussion panels on contemporary issues.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The internationally syndicated radio program *eTown* has its headquarters at eTown Hall, at the intersection of 16th and Spruce Streets, in downtown Boulder.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Most tapings of this weekly show are done at eTown Hall.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Beginning in 1983, hundreds of people head to the Boulder Reservoir on New Year's Day to take part in the annual polar bear plunge.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] With rescue teams standing by, participants use a variety of techniques to plunge themselves into the freezing reservoir.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Starting in 1998, dozens of people have taken part in a Halloween run down the city's streets wearing only shoes and a hollowed-out pumpkin on their heads.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In 2009, local police threatened participants with charges of indecent exposure, and no naked runners were reported in official newscasts, although a few naked runners were observed by locals.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Several illegal attempts, resulting in arrests, have been made to restart the run, but no serious effort has been mounted.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The Happy Thursday Cruiser Ride is a weekly bicycle ride in Boulder Colorado.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The Boulder Cruiser Ride grew from a group of friends and friends of friends in the early '90s riding bicycles around Boulder into the social cycling event it is today.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Some enthusiasts gather wearing costumes and decorating their bikes; themes are an integral part of the cruiser tradition.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder Police began following the cruiser ride as it gained in popularity in the early 2000s.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Issues with underage drinking, reckless bicycle riding, and other nuisance complaints led organizers to drop the cruiser ride as a public event.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Returning to an underground format, where enthusiasts must become part of the social network before gaining access to event sites, the Boulder Cruiser Ride has continued as a local tradition.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] On May 30, 2013, over 400 riders attended the Thursday-night Cruiser Ride in honor of "Big Boy", an elk that was shot and killed on New Year's Day by an on-duty Boulder Police officer.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Each year, the Independent Order of Odd Fellows hosts what they claim is the world's shortest St.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Patrick's Day Parade, which extends just one city block.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Founded in 2005, the Boulder International Film Festival is held annually in March and showcases films in different venues around Boulder, including the Boulder Theater.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Starting in 2027, Boulder will become the new host for the Sundance Film Festival.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Under the terms of the contract, the festival will be held in Boulder for 10 years until 2037, with an option to extend.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder is around 10x larger than the original (and only) host city Sundance was based in, Park City, Utah.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder defeated rival bids from Salt Lake City-Park City and Cincinnati.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder is surrounded by thousands of acres of recreational open space, conservation easements, and nature preserves.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The unincorporated community of Eldorado Springs, south of Boulder, is home to rock climbing routes.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] There are climbing routes available in the city open space, including climbing routes of varying difficulty on the Flatirons themselves (traditional protection).
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder Canyon (sport), directly west of downtown Boulder, has many routes.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] All three of these areas are affected by seasonal closures for wildlife.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Every year on Groundhog Day, Boulder Open Space & Mountain Parks hosts a special event at the Chautauqua Ranger Cottage featuring Flatiron Freddy, a stuffed marmot instead of a groundhog.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder is a home rule municipality, being self-governing under Article XX of the Constitution of the State of Colorado; Title 31, Article 1, Section 202 of the Colorado Revised Statutes.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Politically, Boulder is one of the most liberal and Democratic cities in Colorado when viewed from a Federal and State elections lens.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] As of May 2026, registered voters in Boulder County were 45.2% Democratic, 4.7% Republican, and 50.1% were unaffiliated or a member of minor parties.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] By residents and detractors alike, Boulder is often referred to as the "People's Republic of Boulder".
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In 1974, the Boulder City Council passed Colorado's first ordinance prohibiting discrimination based on sexual orientation.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder voters repealed the measure by referendum within a year.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In 1975, Boulder County Clerk Clela Rorex was the second in the United States ever to grant same-sex marriage licenses, prior to state laws being passed to prevent such issuance.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The city created a community-centered process to focus on energy systems, regenerative ecosystems, circular materials economy, land use, and financial systems.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The Boulder Valley School District (BVSD) administers the public school system in Boulder, aside from a few areas in northeast Boulder, where students attend the St.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Charter schools within the city of Boulder include Preparatory High School (9–12), Summit Middle School (6–8), and Horizons Alternative School (K–8).
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] A variety of private high schools, middle schools and elementary schools operate in Boulder.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder's main daily newspaper, the *Daily Camera*, was founded in 1890 as the weekly *Boulder Camera*, and became a daily newspaper in 1891.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The *Colorado Daily* was started in 1892 as a university newspaper for CU Boulder.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Following many heated controversies over *Colorado Daily*'s political coverage, it severed its ties to the university in 1971.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] From 1996 to 2000, the *Boulder Planet* competed with the *Boulder Weekly* as a free weekly.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Newspaper conglomerate Scripps acquired the *Colorado Daily* in 2005 after its acquisition of the *Camera* in 1997, leaving the *Boulder Weekly* as the only locally owned newspaper in Boulder.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Scripps relinquished its 50 percent ownership in both daily papers in early 2009 to Media News Group.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] *Boulder Magazine*, a lifestyle magazine, was founded in 1978.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] *Boulder Magazine* is published three times per year.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder is part of the Denver market for television stations, and it receives many radio stations based in Denver or Ft.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] For cable television, Boulder is served by Comcast Cable.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The city operates public service Boulder 8 TV on cable (high- and standard-definition), which airs, live-streams and archives council meetings.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] With its in-house video production facilities, it also produces news, talk and informational programming.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Over-the-air television reception is poor in the western part of the city because of interference from mountains.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Non-commercial community radio station KGNU was founded in 1978 and commercial music station KBCO in 1977.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] KBCO programs an adult album alternative format and is owned and operated by iHeartMedia.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] KBCO moved its studios from Boulder to the Denver Tech Center in 2010.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] It maintains the Boulder license and transmits from atop Eldorado Mountain south of Boulder.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] KVCU, also known as Radio 1190, is a non-commercial radio station run with the help of university-student volunteers.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] NPR programming is heard over KCFC 1490 AM, operated by Colorado Public Radio, and simulcasting Denver station KCFR 90.1.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] KRKS-FM 94.7, owned and operated by Salem Media Group and affiliated with SRN News, offers a Christian talk and teaching format, and has its transmitter located on Lee Hill, northwest of Boulder.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The University of Colorado Press, a non-profit co-op of various western universities, publishes academic books, as do Lynne Rienner Publishers, Paradigm Publishers, and Westview Press.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Paladin Press book/video publishers and *Soldier of Fortune* magazine both have their headquarters in Boulder.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Paladin Press was founded in September 1970 by Peder Lund and Robert K.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In 1974, Lund bought out Brown's share of the press, and Brown founded *Soldier of Fortune* magazine in 1975.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Since Boulder has operated under residential growth control ordinances since 1976, new residential construction has been severely limited.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] However, commercial and employment growth has continued, resulting in an imbalance where job growth has far outstripped population growth.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Considerable road traffic enters the city each morning and leaves each afternoon, since many employees live in Longmont, Lafayette, Louisville, Broomfield, Westminster, and Denver.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder is served by US 36 and a variety of state highways.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Parking regulations in Boulder have been explicitly designed to discourage parking by commuters and to encourage the use of mass transit, with mixed results.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Over the years, Boulder has made significant investments in the multi-modal network.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The city is now well known for its grade-separated bicycle and pedestrian paths, which are integrated into a network of bicycle lanes, cycle tracks, and on-street bicycle routes.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder provides a community transit network that connects downtown, the University of Colorado campuses, and local shopping amenities.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Local and regional shuttle busses are funded by a variety of sources.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Due in part to these investments in pedestrian, bicycle, and transit infrastructure, Boulder has been recognized both nationally and internationally for its transportation system.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In 2009, the Boulder metropolitan statistical area (MSA) ranked as the fourth highest in the United States for percentage of commuters who biked to work, at 5.4 percent.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In 2013, the Boulder MSA ranked as the fourth lowest in the United States for percentage of workers who commuted by private automobile, at 71.9 percent.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] During the same time period, 11.1 percent of Boulder area workers had no commute whatsoever: they worked out of the home.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder has an extensive bus system operated by the Regional Transportation District (RTD).
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The HOP, SKIP, JUMP, Bound, DASH and Stampede routes run throughout the city and connect to nearby communities with departures every ten to fifteen minutes during peak hours, Monday-Friday.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Regional routes, traveling between nearby cities such as Longmont (BOLT, J), Golden (GS), and Denver (Flatiron Flyer, a bus rapid transit route), as well as Denver International Airport (AB), are also available.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] There are over 100 scheduled daily bus trips on seven routes that run between Boulder and Denver on weekdays.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Freight service is provided by Union Pacific and BNSF.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Currently there is no intercity passenger service.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The last remaining services connecting the Front Range cities ceased with the formation of Amtrak in 1971.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Front Range Passenger Rail is a current proposal (as of 2023) to link the cities from Pueblo in the south, north to Fort Collins and possibly to Cheyenne, Wyoming.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] A 41-mile (66 km) RTD commuter rail route called the Northwest Rail Line, also known as the B Line, is proposed to run from Denver through Boulder to Longmont, with stops in major communities along the way.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The Boulder station is to be north of Pearl Street and east of 30th Street.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] At one time this commuter rail service was scheduled to commence in 2014, but major delays have ensued.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In 2016, an initial 6-mile (9.7 km) segment opened, reaching from downtown Denver to southern Westminster at Westminster Station.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The remaining 35 miles (56 km) of the Northwest Rail Line is planned to be completed by 2044, depending upon funding.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] These future transit plans, as well as the current Flatiron Flyer Bus Rapid Transit route, are part of FasTracks, an RTD transit improvement plan funded by a 0.4% increase in the sales tax throughout the Denver metro area.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] RTD, the developer of FasTracks, is partnering with the city of Boulder to plan a transit-oriented development near Pearl and 33rd Streets in association with the proposed Boulder commuter rail station.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The development is to feature the Boulder Railroad Depot, already relocated to that site, which may be returned to a transit-related use.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder, well known for its bicycle culture, has hundreds of miles of bicycle-pedestrian paths, lanes, and routes that interconnect to create a renowned network of bikeways usable year-round.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder has 74 bike and pedestrian underpasses that facilitate safer and uninterrupted travel throughout much of the city.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The city offers a route-finding website that allows users to map personalized bike routes around the city, and is one of five communities to have received a "Platinum Bicycle Friendly Community" rating from the League of American Bicyclists.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The headquarters of the free and non-obligatory hospitality exchange network for cyclists, Warm Showers, is based in Boulder.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In May 2011, B-cycle bike-sharing opened in Boulder with 100 red bikes and 12 stations.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder Municipal Airport is located 3 miles (4.8 km) northeast of central Boulder, is owned by the City of Boulder and is used exclusively for general aviation, with most traffic consisting of single-engine airplanes and glider aircraft.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Woody Allen's film *Sleeper* (1973) was filmed on location in Boulder.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Some houses and the Mesa Laboratory of the National Center for Atmospheric Research, designed by I.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder was a setting for Stephen King's book *The Stand* (1978), as the gathering point for some of the survivors of the superflu.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] King lived in Boulder for a little less than a year, beginning in the autumn of 1974, and wrote *The Shining* (1977) during this period.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The television sitcom *Mork & Mindy* (1978–1982) was set in Boulder, with 1619 Pine St. serving as the exterior shot of Mindy's home.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The New York Deli, a now closed restaurant in the Pearl Street Mall, was also featured prominently in the series.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] In the American version of the television sitcom *The Office*, the character Michael Scott leaves the show in season 7 and moves with his fiancée to Boulder.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] "Boulder to Birmingham" is a song written by Emmylou Harris and Bill Danoff which first appeared on Harris's 1975 album *Pieces of the Sky*.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] It has served as something of a signature tune for the artist and recounts her feelings of grief in the years following the death of country rock star and mentor Gram Parsons.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The Comedy Central television show *Broad City* ends with the protagonist, Abby, moving to Boulder for an art fellowship.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Significant parts of the 2006 movie Catch and Release were filmed in Boulder, and includes many well-known Boulder institutions such as Celestial Seasonings, the Boulder Farmer's Market, and Pearl Street Mall.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Landmarks representing Boulder's connection with its various sister cities can be found throughout the city.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Boulder's Sister City Plaza – dedicated on May 17, 2007 – is located on the east lawn of Boulder's Municipal Building.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The plaza was built to honor all of Boulder's sister city relationships.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The Dushanbe Tea House is located on 13th Street just south of the Pearl Street Mall.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] Dushanbe presented its distinctive tea house as a gift to Boulder in 1987.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] It was completed in Tajikistan in 1990 and then shipped to Boulder, where it was reassembled and opened to the public in 1998.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] A mural representing the relationship between Boulder and Mante, Mexico, was dedicated in August 2001.
[src:charles-palache/boulder-colorado] The mural, which was painted by Mante muralist Florian Lopez, is located on the north-facing wall of the Dairy Center for the Performing Arts.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] In 1928, Dorothy Day's conversion to Roman Catholicism marked a pivotal moment where her religious convictions intertwined with her political aspirations.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] This alignment was further solidified when she crossed paths with Peter Maurin, a French immigrant, in 1933.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] Maurin's arrival at Day's home sparked a meeting of minds, as they shared mutual ideas and visions.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] Their collaboration culminated in the establishment of the Catholic Worker Movement, spurred by their shared commitment to nonviolent revolution.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] This movement officially began in 1933 with the inception of *The Catholic Worker* newspaper, a platform they envisioned during their extensive discussions and deliberations.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] Maurin proposed the idea to Day that the newspaper should be tailored for the unemployed.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] Drawing from his knowledge of European socialism and personalist philosophy, Maurin collaborated with Day, leveraging her journalistic skills and understanding of American culture.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] In the initial stages of planning the publication, there was a divergence in opinions between Dorothy Day and Peter Maurin regarding the name of the newspaper.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] Maurin advocated for naming it *The Catholic Radical*, while Day, drawing from her background as a former Communist, believed that *The Catholic Worker* would better resonate with their intended audience.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] She elaborated that the term "Worker" in the paper's title included individuals engaged in physical, mental, or spiritual labor, particularly emphasizing the poor, the dispossessed, and the exploited.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] Maurin wanted the newspaper to be part of a bigger plan for Catholic social action.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] This plan involved a mix of learning to help people think intellectually, regardless of their background.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] It also included setting up places where the needy could get food, shelter, and companionship—called houses of hospitality.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] Maurin also thought about creating farm communities or agronomic universities.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] These places would give land and jobs to people who were struggling because of displacement by industrialisation.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] While many Catholic social action movements in the U.S. focused on issues like public morality, parochial schools, and birth control, the *Catholic Worker* took a different approach.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] Since its first edition in May 1933, the *Catholic Worker* has discussed topics such as racism, pacifism, sweatshops, political corruption, labor unions, antisemitism, fascism, and Catholic social theory.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] The readership increased significantly, and by September 1933, Day and Maurin were printing 20,000 papers.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] By 1935, the circulation of the *Catholic Worker* had risen to 110,000.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] During World War II, the newspaper maintained a relatively high circulation, but it decreased due to its pacifist stance.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] This stance led to internal conflicts within the movement.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] By 1938, the paper's circulation had grown to 190,000.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] However, Dorothy Day's commitment to pacifism caused circulation to drop to 50,000 during the war.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] In her position, Day strongly opposed antisemitism and fascism.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] However, she also criticized the Allies during World War II for failing to acknowledge the presence of Christ in their adversaries or to recognize God's existence amidst evil.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] Day believed that all U.S. citizens carried culpability before God for events like those in Hiroshima.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] She argued that standing in solidarity with all individuals, whether they be poor, allies, or enemies, as part of the mystical body of Christ, also entails sharing responsibility for their actions.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] Following Maurin's passing in 1949, Dorothy Day assumed leadership of the movement and continued to serve as the editor of its newspaper.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] During the 1950s and 1960s, Dorothy Day's engagement with labor issues diminished as her attention shifted towards pacifism and disarmament advocacy.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] Her commitment to nonviolence prompted her to actively protest against the nuclear arms race, the Korean War, and other major conflicts of the time.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] By the 1950s, Day and fellow Catholic Workers believed that mere verbal opposition to war and militarism was insufficient.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] They felt compelled to personally engage and take responsibility for their actions.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] Between 1955 and 1961, Catholic Workers in New York orchestrated acts of civil disobedience aimed at challenging the nuclear arms race, specifically targeting the compulsory annual air raid drills enforced by the Civil Defense Act.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] Between 1947 and early 1960, circulation varied between 47,000 and 65,000 readers.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] Day became increasingly reclusive, reducing her writing output and travel commitments.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] However, she remained involved in editing the newspaper until her death in 1980.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] In both 2020 and 2022, the *Catholic Worker* maintained around 20,000 mail subscribers.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] Additionally, the collective movement has expanded significantly from its origins as a newspaper and a single small house in New York to encompassing 187 communities in a decentralized network, collaborating with numerous partners worldwide.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] According to *The Nation*, as of May 2023, it has approximately 26,000 subscribers.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] According to managing editor Joanne Kennedy, they continue to manually lay out the paper instead of using digital software.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] Additionally, they have consciously opted against having a website or email.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] They have deliberately abstained from releasing a digital edition of the newspaper.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] Daloisio serves as the co-managing editor of *The Catholic Worker*.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] The development of CatholicWorker.org, a website not officially affiliated with the movement but created by Jim Allaire to serve as a digital hub for Catholic Worker communities.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] Despite initial skepticism within the movement about embracing technology, platforms like Instagram and Facebook have become avenues for outreach, connecting younger generations with the movement's values of social justice and hospitality.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] During the early stages of the Catholic Worker movement, there was some resistance among average Catholics in America to embrace the movement and its said alignment with Church teachings.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] This sentiment coincided with a broader societal apprehension towards anything resembling Communism, particularly during the era of the Red Scare.
[src:charles-palache/catholic-worker] Observers, including many Catholics, were skeptical of the Catholic Worker's houses of hospitality, finding it challenging to reconcile the voluntary poverty embraced by its members with traditional Christian teachings.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] Charles Palache came from the Pallache family of Sephardic Jews.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] His grandfather, John Palache, had a plantation in Jamaica.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] His father, James Palache, was born in New York and moved to San Francisco as a merchant.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] He became interested early on in natural history.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] In 1887 he began studies in mining at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] He received his B.S. in 1891 and a doctorate in Mining in 1894 after studying under Andrew C.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] He mapped geologically the territory of the San Francisco Peninsula and from Berkeley and began to be interested in mineralogy.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] In 1894 he went to study in Germany under Ferdinand Zirkel in Leipzig and Ernst Weinschenk in Munich.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] In Heidelberg, he worked with mineralogists Harry Rosenbusch and Alfred Osann and crystallographer Victor Mordechai Goldschmidt.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] In autumn 1895, Palache returned to California.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] He became an instructor in mineralogy, promoted to assistant professor in 1902 and professor in 1910.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] When Wolff retired in 1922, he took over his professorship, faculty, Harvard Mineralogical Laboratory, and Harvard Mineralogical Museum.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] Palache mainly dealt with crystallography, the geometric form of crystals.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] Peacock and Harry Berman (who introduced X-ray crystallographic methods) were important assistants.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] In 1944 with Berman and Clifford Frondel, he produced the 7th edition of *Dana's System of Mineralogy*.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] In 1921, Palache served as president of the Mineralogical Society of America and again in 1950 as honorary president.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] In 1937, he served as president of the Geological Society of America.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] He was a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences (1903).
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] He was also an honorary member of the Mineralogical Society of Great Britain, the New York Academy of Sciences, and the Belgian Geological Society.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] On August 15, 1899, Palache married Helen Markham, "who had traveled from her home in Green Bay, Wisconsin, to California in a caravan of seven covered wagons." They had three daughters: Jeannette Palache Barker (teacher), Mary Palache Gregory (architect, and Alice Palache Jones (banker).
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] Alice was a classmate of American movie star Katharine Hepburn.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] His grandchildren included Judith Palache Gregory, editor of *Catholic Worker* and executor of the will of Dorothy Day.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] Palache's brother Whitney had two sons, James and John.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] Both fought in World War I: James Palache died from his wounds on May 15, 1918.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] Palache died on December 5, 1954, in Charlottesville, Virginia.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] His wife had predeceased him on October 27, 1949.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] Palache was co-editor of the *Journal of Crystallography* and the *American Journal of Science*.
[src:charles-palache/charles-palache] Redpath Museum holds a collection of Palache minerals.
[src:charles-palache/charlesite] Charlesite has only been found in a few specific locations in the world.
[src:charles-palache/charlesite] The first was its place of discovery at Franklin Mine in Franklin, Sussex County, New Jersey.
[src:charles-palache/charlesite] It was located immediately above the 800 level, about 15 feet into the ore from the hanging wall.
[src:charles-palache/charlesite] The ore mostly consisted of franklinite and willemite and several other minor minerals.
[src:charles-palache/charlesite] The crystals found at this location were up to 6mm in length and were suspected to have grown alongside clinohedrite crystals.
[src:charles-palache/charlesite] The other location where charlesite has been located is the Wessel's Mine, N' Chwaning Mines, and Kalahari Manganese Fields in Northern Cape Province, South Africa.
[src:charles-palache/charlesite] The Wessel's Mine is thought to be the only source for charlesite to be found in gem quality.
[src:charles-palache/charlesite] Several other recorded places are Germany, Japan, Norway, Romania, and Slovakia.
[src:charles-palache/charlesite] Due to its rarity, there are very few uses for charlesite.
[src:charles-palache/charlesite] Though there is not much of the mineral, one of the major uses for specimens that meet the necessary standards is gems.
[src:charles-palache/charlesite] Due to its softness, it will not be found in much jewelry.
[src:charles-palache/charlesite] Some other uses could be for studying the reasons for the rarity of the mineral, teaching mineralogy classes, or even serving as items for collectors or museums of rare minerals.
